  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        One way of defining the natural logarithm is
        <me>
          \ln x=\int_{1}^{x}\frac{1}{t}\dd{t}
        </me>.
        You can then show that this function has all the properties you'd expect of the natural logarithm.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Many functions don't have closed-form antiderivatives! But we do something very similar to deal with them<mdash/>we define a new function.
        A few examples:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Logarithmic integral:
              <me>
                \mathrm{li}(x)=\int_{0}^{x}\frac{1}{\ln t}\dd{t}
              </me>
              This is used in number theory.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Fresnel integrals:
            </p>
            <md>
              <mrow>\mathrm{S}(x) \amp = \int_{0}^{x}\sin(t^{2})\dd{t}</mrow>
              <mrow> \mathrm{C}(x) \amp = \int_{0}^{x}\cos(t^{2})\dd{t}</mrow>
            </md>

            <p>
              These are used in optics.
              Also there's lots of cool stuff related to the Euler spiral, parametric stuff from Chapter 6, and a connection to roller coasters!
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
